# C# in All Space — ProjectileManager Only

C# is used exclusively for `ProjectileManager.cs`. This is the only C# file in the
entire project. If you're creating a new `.cs` file that isn't ProjectileManager,
stop and reconsider — it should probably be GDScript.

## Why C# Here
The dumb projectile pool (bullets, energy pulses) processes potentially thousands of
entities per frame. C# provides 2-5x performance improvement for tight math loops
compared to GDScript. Guided projectiles (missiles) use a separate GDScript pool
because they're fewer in number and need tighter Godot integration.

## GDScript ↔ C# Bridge
- `ServiceLocator.cs` provides the service registry
- Communication between C# and GDScript goes through `GameEventBus` signals
- ProjectileManager registers itself with ServiceLocator on `_Ready()`
- GDScript weapon components call into ProjectileManager to spawn projectiles

## Conventions
- Follow C# naming conventions (PascalCase methods, camelCase locals)
- Use object pooling — never allocate projectiles at runtime
- Keep the public API surface small — GDScript only needs spawn/despawn
- Instrument with PerformanceMonitor (the GDScript singleton is accessible from C#)
